## Chapter 2 Review: Functions and Files

This chapter introduced the core building block of C++ program structure: functions. Here is what you covered.

### Functions and return values

As shown in "Introduction to functions" and "Function return values," every function has a return type, a name, and a body. Value-returning functions use `return` to send a result back to the caller; void functions ("Void functions") perform side effects and return nothing.

### Parameters and scope

"Introduction to function parameters and arguments" showed how to pass data into functions — always by value unless explicitly changed later. "Introduction to local scope" established that variables declared inside a function (or block) are destroyed when the block ends. This is stricter than Python's function scope; C++ has *block* scope.

### Program organization

"Forward declarations and definitions" solved the top-to-bottom compilation constraint. "Programs with multiple code files" extended this to separate `.cpp` files linked together. "Header files" and "Header guards" formalized the pattern: declarations go in `.h` files protected by `#ifndef` or `#pragma once`.

### Namespaces and the preprocessor

"Naming collisions and an introduction to namespaces" explained why `std::` exists. "Introduction to the preprocessor" covered `#include`, `#define`, and conditional compilation — the text substitution phase that runs before the compiler sees your code.

### Putting it together

"How to design your first programs" capped the chapter with a top-down strategy: define the problem, break it into functions, implement one at a time.

```cpp
#include <iostream>

int square(int n) { return n * n; }
int sumOfSquares(int a, int b) { return square(a) + square(b); }

int main()
{
    int x{};
    int y{};
    std::cin >> x >> y;
    std::cout << sumOfSquares(x, y) << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

This example combines value-returning functions, parameters, local scope, forward-compatible ordering, and `std::` — every concept from the chapter in under 15 lines.

